Western Cape Health MEC Nomafrench Mbombo says the emergency call centre received more than 64,000 calls in December last year. CAPE TOWN The Western Cape Health Department says its emergency services are prepared for the festive season.The department today briefed the media on efforts to address an expected increase in the demand for emergency assistance during the holidays.Western Cape Health MEC Nomafrench Mbombo says staff are inundated with emergency calls during the festive season.Mbombo says the emergency call centre received more than 64,000 calls in December last year.This is an increase of more than 10,000 compared to December 2012.Other festive season 'trends' highlighted by Mbombo, include increases in road fatalities, near drownings and drowning incidents at swimming facilities and beaches, and interpersonal violence related injuries.The festive season operational plan will be implemented until March.(Edited by Neo Koza)